description:
In lichen_l2.c:274-281 (lichen_l2_recv), the code validates iface, then marks it unused:

```c
if (iface == NULL) {
    LOG_ERR("lichen_l2_recv: iface is NULL");
    return NET_DROP;
}

ARG_UNUSED(iface);
ARG_UNUSED(pkt);
```

This is technically correct (the parameter IS used for validation but not for any functional logic), but reads as contradictory. A future reader might think the NULL check is dead code.

What goes wrong: Cognitive overhead during code review. Someone might remove the 'redundant' NULL check thinking ARG_UNUSED means the parameter truly isn't used.

Suggested fix: Remove ARG_UNUSED(iface) since it IS used for validation, or add a comment explaining the pattern.
